>>>>> In article <PCL.93Feb11151605@rhodium.ox.ac.uk>, pcl@ox.ac.uk
>>>>> (Paul C Leyland) writes:

Paul> In article <C1q1y1.A5q@vti.com> cpcahil@vti.com (Conor P. Cahill) writes:

Paul>    I'm not a cryptographer, so I may be totally off the wall, but it
Paul>        ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
Paul>    seems to me that the security of the data would be more at risk 
Paul>    if you use RSA for the entire encryption mechanism.

Paul>    I base this on the assumption that the more data that is available 
Paul>    that has been encrypted by the encryption algorithm, the more likely

Paul> Justify this assumption.  You might be correct, but I don't find
Paul> it obvious.

Paul>    it is going to be broken.  This is especially true if the data is
Paul>    somewhat predictable (a paragraph, shuch as this one, is much more
Paul>    predictable than a random sequence of bytes).

Paul> Justify this assumption as well.

Hey, don't ask the man to do impossible things :-)  The point is, RSA
is a public-key system, so given the public key, anyone can generate
as many plaintext/ciphertext pairs as they wish.  Clearly, giving them
some more data of the same form isn't going to help the attacker.

- Harald
